men.data %>% select(lose.odds.col.nums) %>% apply(1, function(x) sum(!is.na(x))) -> men.data$countLoseOdds

# new variable: maximum odds for the loser
men.data %>% select(lose.odds.col.nums) %>% apply(1, function(x) max(x, na.rm = T) )-> men.data$maxLoseOdds

# new variabe: maxiumum odds for the winner

# new variable: minimum odds for the loser

Baseline strategies

The purpose of this is to provide the results to the two baseline strategies: 1. Always betting the favorite (average book) 2. Always betting the underdog (average book) 3. Randomly betting the underdog or favorite (average book) 4. Always betting the higher ranked player (average book) 5. Always betting the lower ranked player (average book) 6. Always betting the favorite (highest book) 7. Always betting the underdog (highest book) 8. Randomly betting the underdog or favorite (highest book) 9. Always betting the higher ranked player (highest book) 10. Always betting the lower ranked player (highest book)

I will run this simulation seperately for each of the years from 2001 through 2017 in order to look for trends that may provide insight in how the oddsmakers have adapted over the years.

Baseline Strategy 1: always bet favorite average book
#### Function for single-year simulation
bet.favorite <- function(df, wager = 10){
  # initialize
  net <- 0
  tries <- 0
  wins <- 0
  
  # for each match:
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){
    
    # if chalk (win)
    if(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE){
      bet.result <- wager * (df$avgF[i]-1)
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      wins <- wins + 1
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if upset (loss)
    if(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE){
      bet.result <- -1*wager
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
  }
  
  # output a list
  out <- list(net, wins, tries)
  names(out) <- c("net","wins","tries")
  return(out)
}

#### Loop through all the seasons
for(i in 1:length(Year)){
  season <- data %>% filter(year == Year[i])
  s.result <- bet.favorite(season, wager = 10)
  
  df1$Net[i] <- s.result[[1]]
  df1$Wins[i] <- s.result[[2]]
  df1$Tries[i] <- s.result[[3]]
}
names(df1)[2] <- "Strategy"

#### Function for single-year simulation
bet.random <- function(df, wager = 10){
  # initialize
  net <- 0
  tries <- 0
  wins <- 0
  
  # for each match:
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){
    
    choice <- sample(c("fav","dog"),size=1)
    
    if(choice == "dog"){

      # if upset (win)
      if(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE){
        bet.result <- wager * (df$avgU[i]-1)
        
        net <- net + bet.result

        wins <- wins + 1
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
      
      # if chalk (loss)
      if(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE){
        bet.result <- -1*wager
        
        net <- net + bet.result
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
    }
    
    if(choice == "fav"){

      # if chalk (win)
      if(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE){
        bet.result <- wager * (df$avgF[i]-1)
  
        net <- net + bet.result
        wins <- wins + 1
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
      
      # if upset (loss)
      if(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE){
        bet.result <- -1*wager
        
        net <- net + bet.result
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
    }
  }
  
  # output a list
  out <- list(net, wins, tries)
  
  names(out) <- c("net","wins","tries")
  return(out)
}

Baseline Strategy 4: always bet the higher ranked player (average book)
#### Function for single-year simulation
bet.highrank <- function(df, wager = 10){
  # initialize
  net <- 0
  tries <- 0
  wins <- 0
  
  # for each match:
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){

    if(df$rank.upset[i] == FALSE){

      # if 'chalk' and higher rank (win)
      if(df$odds.upset[i]==FALSE){
        bet.result <- wager * (df$avgF[i]-1)
        
        net <- net + bet.result
        wins <- wins + 1
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
    
      # if 'dog' and higher rank (win)
      if(df$odds.upset[i]==TRUE){
        bet.result <- wager * (df$avgU[i]-1)
        
        net <- net + bet.result
        wins <- wins + 1
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
    }
    
    if(df$rank.upset[i] == TRUE){

      # if 'chalk' and lower rank (loss)
      if(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE){
        bet.result <- -1*wager
        
        net <- net + bet.result
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
    
      # if 'dog' and lower rank (loss)
      if(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE){
        bet.result <- -1*wager
        
        net <- net + bet.result
        tries <- tries + 1
      }
    }
  }
  
  # output a list
  out <- list(net, wins, tries)
  names(out) <- c("net","wins","tries")
  return(out)
}

  season <- data %>% filter(year == Year[i])

Baseline Strategy 5: always bet the lower ranked player (average book)
#### Function for single-year simulation
bet.lowrank <- function(df, wager = 10){
  # initialize
  net <- 0
  tries <- 0
  wins <- 0
  
  # for each match:
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){
    
    # if 'chalk' and lower rank (win)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == TRUE)&(df$odds.upset[i]==FALSE)){
      bet.result <- wager * (df$avgF[i]-1)
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      wins <- wins + 1
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if 'dog' and lower rank (win)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == TRUE)&(df$odds.upset[i]==TRUE)){
      bet.result <- wager * (df$avgU[i]-1)
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      wins <- wins + 1
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if 'chalk' and higher rank (loss)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == FALSE)&(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE)){
      bet.result <- -1*wager
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if 'dog' and higher rank (win)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == FALSE)&(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE)){
      bet.result <- -1*wager
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
  }
  
  # output a list
  out <- list(net, wins, tries)
  names(out) <- c("net","wins","tries")
  return(out)
}

  df8$Tries[i] <- s.result[[3]]
}
names(df8)[2] <- "Strategy"
Baseline Strategy 9: always bet the higher ranked player (highest book)
#### Function for single-year simulation
bet.highrank.h <- function(df, wager = 10){
  # initialize
  net <- 0
  tries <- 0
  wins <- 0
  
  # for each match:
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){
    
    # if 'chalk' and higher rank (win)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == FALSE)&(df$odds.upset[i]==FALSE)){
      bet.result <- wager * (df$FMaxOdds[i]-1)
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      wins <- wins + 1
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if 'dog' and higher rank (win)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == FALSE)&(df$odds.upset[i]==TRUE)){
      bet.result <- wager * (df$UMaxOdds[i]-1)
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      wins <- wins + 1
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if 'chalk' and lower rank (loss)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == TRUE)&(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE)){
      bet.result <- -1*wager
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
    
    # if 'dog' and lower rank (loss)
    if((df$rank.upset[i] == TRUE)&(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE)){
      bet.result <- -1*wager
      
      net <- net + bet.result
      tries <- tries + 1
    }
  }
  
  # output a list
  out <- list(net, wins, tries)
  names(out) <- c("net","wins","tries")
  return(out)
}

  df9$Tries[i] <- s.result[[3]]

Gambling Strategy Simulation

Strategy based on Payout-Potential Measure

### Payout-Potenial Strategy Function
nick.strategy <- function(df, wager = 10){

  # initialize
  net <- 0
  tries <- 0
  wins <- 0
  
  # Vector of decision requirements - series
  bet.fav.series <- c("Grand Slam", "International Series", "Masters Cup")
  bet.dog.series <- c("Masters 1000")
  # Vector of baseline betting requirements - series
  bet.series <- c(bet.fav.series, bet.dog.series, "ATP250", "ATP500", "Masters")
  
  # Vector of decision requirements - game
  bet.fav.games <- c(5)
  bet.dog.games <- c()
  # Vector of baseline betting requirements - game
  bet.games <- c(bet.fav.games, 3)
  
  # Vector of decision requirements - surface
  bet.fav.surface <- c("Grass")
  bet.dog.surface <- c("Carpet")
  # Vector of baseline betting requirements - surface
  bet.surface <- c(bet.fav.surface, bet.dog.surface, "Hard", "Clay")
  
  # Vector of decision requirements - round
  bet.fav.round <- c("4th Round", "The Final")
  bet.dog.round <- c()
  # Vector of baseline betting requirements - round
  bet.round <- c(bet.fav.round,"Quarterfinals", "Semifinals")
  
  
  # Loop for betting decisions
  for(i in 1:nrow(df)){
    
    # Match must meet all baseline betting requirements
    if((df$Series[i] %in% bet.series) & (df$Best.of[i] %in% bet.games) & (df$Surface[i] %in% bet.surface) & (df$Round[i] %in% bet.round)){
    
 
      # BET UNDERDOG if any underdog decision requirement met
      if((df$Series[i] %in% bet.dog.series) | (df$Best.of[i] %in% bet.dog.games) | (df$Surface[i] %in% bet.dog.surface) | (df$Round[i] %in% bet.dog.round)){
        
        # place wager on UMaxOdds
        
        # if win
        if(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE){
          bet.result <- wager * (df$UMaxOdds[i]-1)
          
          net <- net + bet.result
          wins <- wins + 1
          tries <- tries + 1
        }
        
        #if loss
        if(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE){
          bet.result <- -1*wager
          
          net <- net + bet.result
          tries <- tries + 1
        }
      }
      
      # BET FAVORITE if any favorite decision requirement met
      else if((df$Series[i] %in% bet.fav.series) | (df$Best.of[i] %in% bet.fav.games) | (df$Surface[i] %in% bet.fav.surface) | (df$Round[i] %in% bet.fav.round)){
        
        # place wager on FMaxOdds
        
        # if win
        if(df$odds.upset[i] == FALSE){
          bet.result <- wager * (df$FMaxOdds[i]-1)
          
          net <- net + bet.result
          wins <- wins + 1
          tries <- tries + 1
        }
        
        #if loss
        if(df$odds.upset[i] == TRUE){
          bet.result <- -1*wager
          
          net <- net + bet.result
          tries <- tries + 1
        }
      }
    }
  }
  
  # RETURN LIST
  out <- list(net, wins, tries)
  names(out) <- c("net","wins","tries")
  return(out)
}

A potential betting strategy that could work effectively is to be selective in the matches that you bet on, and only bet when you believe that the player has a very high probability of winning the match. A way to do this is use a logistic regression model for a given player and only bet if the model predicts that they have at least a certain probability of winning given different variables such as surface type, rank difference, and odds.

Below I create a function that simulates betting on the 2015, 2016, and 2017 seasons for a given player and runs a logistic regression model that predicts the probability of the given player of winning the match. The logistic regression model uses the 2001 to 2014 seasons as training data for each player. We will use the logistic regression model to look at different net payoffs if the minimum threshold for the winning probability in our betting strategy is changed.

#function that simulates betting on 2015,2016, and 2017 seasons for a given player and runs a logistic regression to predict probability the player wins the match

player.logistic.simulation <- function(playerName, wager=10){
  #filter data frame to games containing a specific player and seperate into training & testing data
  player.train <- filter(men.data, (Winner %in% playerName | Loser %in% playerName) & Date <= "2014-12-31")
  player.test <- filter(men.data, (Winner %in% playerName | Loser %in% playerName) & Date >="2014-12-31")

  #create variable with outcome of game for player
  player.train$Outcome <- (player.train$Winner == playerName)
  player.train$Outcome <- as.numeric(player.train$Outcome)
  player.test$Outcome <- (player.test$Winner == playerName)
  player.test$Outcome <- as.numeric(player.test$Outcome)
  
  #create variable for odds, rank difference, and point difference of player in both testing and training data frames
  for(i in 1:dim(player.train)[1]){
    if(((player.train$Outcome[i] == 1))){
    player.train$Odds[i] <- player.train$avgW[i]
    player.train$RankDif[i] <- player.train$WRank[i]-player.train$LRank[i]
    player.train$PtDif[i] <- player.train$WPts[i] -player.train$LPts[i]
  }
    else{
    player.train$Odds[i] <- player.train$avgL[i]
    player.train$RankDif[i] <- player.train$LRank[i]-player.train$WRank[i]
    player.train$PtDif[i] <- -1*player.train$WPts[i] +player.train$LPts[i]
  }
}
  for(i in 1:dim(player.test)[1]){
    if(((player.test$Outcome[i] == 1))){
      player.test$Odds[i] <- player.test$avgW[i]
      player.test$RankDif[i] <- player.test$WRank[i]-player.test$LRank[i]
      player.test$PtDif[i] <- player.test$WPts[i] -player.test$LPts[i]
    }
    else{
      player.test$Odds[i] <- player.test$avgL[i]
      player.test$RankDif[i] <- player.test$LRank[i]-player.test$WRank[i]
      player.test$PtDif[i] <- -1*player.test$WPts[i] +player.test$LPts[i]
    }
  }
  
  

  #create logistic regression model using training data
  player.glm <- bayesglm(Outcome ~ Surface+Odds+RankDif+Best.of+Series+PtDif, family=binomial, data=player.train,drop.unused.levels   = FALSE)
  
  #format testing data to be able to input into predict.glm
  player.test <- subset(player.test, select=c("year","Surface","Odds","Outcome","Series","RankDif","PtDif","Best.of"))
  prob.win <- predict.glm(player.glm, newdata=subset(player.test,select=c("Surface","Odds","Series","RankDif","PtDif","Best.of")),type = "response")
  

  #attach predicted probability of winning
  player.test$prob <- as.numeric(prob.win)
  player.test$year <- as.factor(player.test$year)
  
  #payoff of match if we bet
  player.test <- mutate(player.test, payoff= Outcome*wager*(Odds-1))
  player.test$payoff[player.test$Outcome==0] <- -1*wager

  player.summary <- summary(player.glm)
  
  
  #output information regarding betting simulation
  out <- player.test
  return(out)
  }

Since the model is based solely on historic performance, it will only work effectively on players who have a larger history for the model to be based on. Therefore, I will run the simulation on all players in the current top 15 who are ages 29 and above. Below I run the simulation for these players and display the results of the simulations for if I had only bet on games in which the player had at least a 0.85, 0.875, or 0.9 probability of winning from the logistic regression’s predictions.

With this betting strategy, a new loss occurred when setting the probability minimum probability of winning a match for matches we would bet on at 0.85 and 0.9. A profit of $31.3825 was won on on 423 bets when the minimum probability was set at 0.875. The model predicts the outcome of the matches fairly accurately as seen in the win percentages of the data frames above. This accurate prediction of the probability of winning does not translate to net winnings that are very high because you are most likely placing bets when the payoff for being correct is not that high. Therefore, even if your bet is wrong only a small percentage of the time as it is above, the loss of your wager for these few incorrect bets is close to the amount of gain you have from all of your correct predictions. This also shows that always betting on the favorite or those who are ranked higher will not work. There will sometimes be matches in which a heavily favored player loses, so betting on safe matches will not work effectively. Being risk averse and only betting on the safe matches does not translate to winnings.

imputed.data <- men.data

  imputed.data[[col.name]]<- as.factor(imputed.data[[col.name]])
}

#List of odds books columns
favorite.columns <- c("B365F", "B.WF" , "CBF" , "EXF" , "LBF" , "GBF" , "IWF" , "PSF" , "SBF" , "SJF" , "UBF" )
underdog.columns <- c("B365U", "B.WU" , "CBU" , "EXU" , "LBU" , "GBU" , "IWU" , "PSU" , "SBU" , "SJU" , "UBU")

#replace all null value books with the average over all books for that match
for(col.name in favorite.columns){
  imputed.data[[col.name]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])] <- imputed.data[["avgF"]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])]

  imputed.data[[col.name]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])] <- imputed.data[["avgU"]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])]

#Function for plotting winnings over time
plot.winnings <- function(df, title){
  df.new.pred <- df %>% dplyr::filter(is.finite(winnings)) %>% arrange(date.new) %>% mutate(winnings = cumsum(winnings))
  plot.df <- ggplot(df.new.pred, aes(date.new, winnings))  + geom_line(color='orange3', size=1) + xlab("Date") + ylab("Winnings") + ggtitle(title)
  
  print(plot.df)
}

  train.end.date <- paste0(i-1, "-01-01", sep = '')

  test.data <- imputed.data %>% dplyr::filter(date.new > as.Date(test.start.date), date.new < as.Date(test.end.date))
  
  #Make predictive models
  
  rf.model = randomForest(favorite_won~., data=new.train, ntree=20, proximity=T)

  #SVM
  svm.model <- svm(favorite_won~., data = new.train)
  
  #Log Reg
  reg.model <- glm(favorite_won ~.,family=binomial(link='logit'),data=new.train)
  
  #Addaboost
  boost.model <- adaboost(favorite_won ~., new.train, nIter = 20)
                   
  
  #Get boolean true false whether model predicts an upset or not
  rf.prediction = predict(rf.model, newdata=test.data)
  svm.prediction <- predict(svm.model, test.data)

                                             TRUE ~ NA_real_))
  svm.bets <- svm.pred %>% mutate( winnings = case_when(prediction != favorite_won ~-bet,
                                             prediction == "TRUE" & favorite_won == prediction  ~ bet * (FMaxOdds -1),
                                             prediction == "FALSE" & favorite_won == prediction ~ bet * (UMaxOdds -1),
                                             TRUE ~ NA_real_))
  reg.bets <- reg.pred %>% mutate( winnings = case_when(prediction != favorite_won ~-bet,
                                             prediction == "TRUE" & favorite_won == prediction  ~ bet * (FMaxOdds -1),
                                             prediction == "FALSE" & favorite_won == prediction ~ bet * (UMaxOdds -1),
                                             TRUE ~ NA_real_))
  boost.bets <- boost.pred %>% mutate( winnings = case_when(prediction != favorite_won ~-bet,
                                             prediction == "TRUE" & favorite_won == prediction  ~ bet * (FMaxOdds -1),
                                             prediction == "FALSE" & favorite_won == prediction ~ bet * (UMaxOdds -1),
                                             TRUE ~ NA_real_))
  
  
  #Plot winnings over time for each model

  plot.winnings(rf.bets, paste(test.start.date, "Random Forest Winnings"))
  plot.winnings(svm.bets, paste(test.start.date, "Support Vector Machine Winnings"))
  plot.winnings(reg.bets, paste(test.start.date, "Logistic Regression Winnings"))
  plot.winnings(boost.bets, paste(test.start.date, "AdaBoost Winnings"))

  #append final payouts
  rf.final.payouts <-  c(rf.final.payouts, sum(rf.bets$winnings))
  svm.final.payouts <-  c(svm.final.payouts, sum(svm.bets$winnings))
  reg.final.payouts <-  c(reg.final.payouts, sum(reg.bets$winnings))
  boost.final.payouts <-  c(boost.final.payouts, sum(boost.bets$winnings))
  
  #make aggregate table
  agg.table <- rf.bets %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "Random Forest",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(rf.bets$prediction == rf.bets$favorite_won))
  agg.table <- agg.table %>%
     rbind(svm.bets  %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "SVM",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(svm.bets$prediction ==svm.bets$favorite_won))) %>%
    rbind(reg.bets  %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "Log reg",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(reg.bets$prediction ==reg.bets$favorite_won))) %>%
  rbind(boost.bets  %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "Boost",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(boost.bets$prediction ==boost.bets$favorite_won)))

  agg.table <- agg.table %>%mutate(success.rate = successful.bets / count, average.payout = net.profit / count)
  print(agg.table)
}

Use Models to predict how much money you will win if you bet on favorite or underdog

First we need to change imputed data for our new prediction column

#create new dataframe to impute
imputed.data <- men.data

#add favorite_won column used to predict winner
imputed.data$favorite_won <- as.factor(!imputed.data$odds.upset)

#Convert characters to factors
character.columns <- c("Location", "Tournament", "Series", "Surface", "Court","Round" )
for(col.name in character.columns){
  imputed.data[[col.name]]<- as.factor(imputed.data[[col.name]])
}

#List of odds books columns
favorite.columns <- c("B365F", "B.WF" , "CBF" , "EXF" , "LBF" , "GBF" , "IWF" , "PSF" , "SBF" , "SJF" , "UBF" )
underdog.columns <- c("B365U", "B.WU" , "CBU" , "EXU" , "LBU" , "GBU" , "IWU" , "PSU" , "SBU" , "SJU" , "UBU")

#replace all null value books with the average over all books for that match
for(col.name in favorite.columns){
  imputed.data[[col.name]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])] <- imputed.data[["avgF"]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])]
}
for(col.name in underdog.columns){
  imputed.data[[col.name]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])] <- imputed.data[["avgU"]][is.na(imputed.data[[col.name]])]
}

#remove any remaining null values, and grab only the columns that we can use in our models
imputed.data <- imputed.data %>% na.omit() %>% select(-maxWinOdds, -minLoseOdds, -maxProfit, -rank.upset, -odds.upset, -Tournament, -Location)
#create a column for rank difference
imputed.data <- imputed.data %>% mutate(rank.diff = abs( URank - FRank))

#note if you change this vaue here and not above, it will be difficult to compare between methods
bet <- 10

#make payout columns and select columns ou need
imputed.data <- imputed.data %>% na.omit() %>% mutate(payout.favorite = case_when(favorite_won == "TRUE"  ~ bet * ( FMaxOdds - 1), favorite_won =="FALSE" ~ -bet, TRUE ~ NA_real_), payout.underdog = case_when(favorite_won == "FALSE"  ~ bet * ( UMaxOdds - 1), favorite_won =="TRUE" ~ -bet, TRUE ~ NA_real_)) 

# choose payout column to be the underdog(can switch to favorite in mutate)
imputed.data <- imputed.data %>% mutate(payout = payout.underdog) %>% select(-payout.favorite, -payout.underdog, -favorite_won)

Now run the Regression tests

rf.final.payouts = c()
svm.final.payouts =c()
reg.final.payouts = c()
for(i in 2011:2017){
  #create date strings to use to limit training and testing datasets
  train.start.date <-  paste0(i-3, "-01-01", sep = '')
  train.end.date <- paste0(i-1, "-01-01", sep = '')
  test.start.date <- paste0(i, "-01-01", sep = '')
  test.end.date <- paste0(i+1, "-01-01", sep = '')
  
  print(test.start.date)
  
  #create training and testing data
  new.train <- imputed.data %>% dplyr::filter(date.new < as.Date(train.end.date), date.new >= as.Date(train.start.date)) 
  test.data <- imputed.data %>% dplyr::filter(date.new > as.Date(test.start.date), date.new < as.Date(test.end.date))

  #Make predictive models
  
  rf.model <-  randomForest(payout~., data=new.train, ntree=20, proximity=T)
  
  #SVM
  svm.model <- svm(payout~., data = new.train)
  
  #Log Reg
  reg.model <- glm(payout ~.,data=new.train)
  
  
  
  
  rf.prediction <- predict(rf.model, newdata=test.data)
  svm.prediction <- predict(svm.model, test.data)
  reg.prediction <- predict(reg.model, test.data)


  #Make data with prediction column
  
  #random forest
  rf.pred <- test.data
  rf.pred$prediction <- rf.prediction
  
  #SVM
  svm.pred <- test.data
  svm.pred$prediction <- svm.prediction
  
  #Log Regression
  reg.pred <- test.data
  reg.pred$prediction <- reg.prediction
  
  # print(paste("rf R.squared: ", cor(test.data$payout,rf.prediction ) ^ 2))
  # print(paste("SVM R.squared: ", cor(test.data$payout,svm.prediction ) ^ 2))
  # print(paste("Logistic R.squared: ", cor(test.data$payout,reg.prediction ) ^ 2))
  
  #View the predictions and results in order of highest expected return
  rf.pred.group <- rf.pred %>% group_by(prediction, payout) %>% summarize(count = n()) %>% arrange(desc(prediction))
  svm.pred.group <- svm.pred %>% group_by(prediction, payout) %>% summarize(count = n()) %>% arrange(desc(prediction))
  reg.pred.group <- reg.pred %>% group_by(prediction, payout) %>% summarize(count = n()) %>% arrange(desc(prediction))

  # print(rf.pred.group)
  # print(svm.pred.group)
  # print(reg.pred.group)

  
  #make bets, here you can filter for when predicted winnings are greate than some threshold.
  rf.bets <- rf.pred %>% mutate( winnings = payout) %>% dplyr::filter(prediction > 2)
  svm.bets <- svm.pred %>% mutate( winnings = payout) %>% dplyr::filter(prediction > 2)
  reg.bets <- reg.pred %>% mutate( winnings = payout) %>% dplyr::filter(prediction > 2)

  #plot winnings
  plot.winnings(rf.bets, paste(test.start.date, "Random Forest Payout"))
  plot.winnings(svm.bets, paste(test.start.date, "Support Vector Machine Payout"))
  plot.winnings(reg.bets, paste(test.start.date, "Logistic Regression payout"))
 
  
  #append final payouts
  rf.final.payouts <-  c(rf.final.payouts, sum(rf.bets$winnings))
  svm.final.payouts <-  c(svm.final.payouts, sum(svm.bets$winnings))
  reg.final.payouts <-  c(reg.final.payouts, sum(reg.bets$winnings))
  
  #create aggregate table
  agg.table <- rf.bets %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "Random Forest",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(rf.bets$winnings > 0))
  agg.table <- agg.table %>%
     rbind(svm.bets  %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "SVM",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(svm.bets$winnings > 0))) %>%
    rbind(reg.bets  %>% summarise(test.start.date =test.start.date, method = "Log reg",count = n(), net.profit = sum(winnings), successful.bets = sum(reg.bets$winnings > 0))) 
  
  print(agg.table)
}
